You are working on the Anvara Sponsorship Marketplace, a full-stack monorepo take-home assessment project.

## Project Structure

- `apps/frontend/` — Next.js 16, React 19, Tailwind CSS v4, Better Auth
- `apps/backend/` — Express 5, Prisma 7, PostgreSQL
- `packages/config/` — Shared TypeScript config
- `packages/eslint-config/` — Shared ESLint 9 config
- `packages/prettier-config/` — Shared Prettier config

## Key Commands

- `pnpm dev` — Start all services
- `pnpm test` — Run Vitest tests
- `pnpm lint` — Lint all packages
- `pnpm typecheck` — TypeScript type checking
- `pnpm --filter @anvara/backend db:generate` — Generate Prisma client
- `pnpm --filter @anvara/backend db:push` — Push schema to DB

## Code Style

- ESM modules (`"type": "module"`) — use `.js` extensions in backend imports
- TypeScript strict mode — avoid `any` types, add proper type annotations
- Prisma generated client at `apps/backend/src/generated/prisma/`
- Routes export Express Router instances from `apps/backend/src/routes/`
- Frontend API client in `apps/frontend/lib/api.ts` — fetch-based, calls backend at port 4291
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes for styling, no CSS modules
- Follow existing Prettier config (`@anvara/prettier-config`)

## Database

- PostgreSQL 16 via Docker on port 5498
- Schema in `apps/backend/prisma/schema.prisma`
- Core models: Sponsor, Publisher, Campaign, Creative, AdSlot, Placement, Payment
- Prisma 7 with `@prisma/adapter-pg` driver adapter

## Authentication

- Better Auth configured in `apps/frontend/auth.ts` (server) and `auth-client.ts` (client)
- Backend auth middleware in `apps/backend/src/auth.ts` (placeholder — needs implementation)
- Two roles: Sponsor and Publisher
- Demo accounts: `sponsor@example.com` / `publisher@example.com` (password: `password`)

## Environment

- `.env` at repo root (see `.env.example`)
- Frontend port: 3847, Backend port: 4291, DB port: 5498

## Important Notes

- This is an assessment project with intentional bugs and TODOs — see `docs/challenges/` for details
- Check `FIXME`, `TODO`, and `BUG` comments for known issues that candidates should address
- When fixing TypeScript errors, prefer strict typing over `any`
- When adding features, follow existing patterns in the codebase
